<ChapterLayout title="Reference Index" headVoice="publisher">
                <div data-voice="publisher">
        <BinderHoles />
        <Backlink />
                    <h2><span>(An Appendix of Terms)</span></h2>
                    <blockquote>
                        <p><span>A quick reference for the terms used throughout </span><a
                                href="/a-severed-story">A Severed Story</a><span>. Each entry
                                points back to the
                                chapter where it is taught in full — follow it there for the complete treatment.</span>
                        </p>
                    </blockquote>
                    <hr />
                    <h1><span>Glossary</span></h1>
                    <hr />
                    <p><strong><span>A Severed Story.</span></strong><span> This game — a
                            handbook of life
                            and joyful labor on a Lumon severed floor, and the rules for playing it. See the </span><a
                            href="/preamble">Preamble</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Boon.</span></strong><span> A standing benefit earned upon
                            reaching a
                            new Tier in a row. See </span><a href="/performance-evaluation">Performance
                            Evaluation</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Burnout.</span></strong><span> What befalls an employee
                            whose stress
                            fills every box. Burnout earns a Demerit. See </span><a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Confidence.</span></strong><span> A favorable Roll: throw
                            2d20 and take
                            the </span><em><span>higher</span></em><span> die. Granted when a Roll falls under one of an
                            employee&#x27;s
                            Core Competencies. See </span><a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural
                            Guidelines</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Core Competency.</span></strong><span> A Core Principle an
                            employee is
                            especially practiced in, marked on the LIEP. Rolls made under it are made with Confidence.
                            See </span><a href="/employee-profile">Employee
                            Profile</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Core Principle.</span></strong><span> One of the Nine
                            practiced virtues
                            of Lumon. Every Roll is made under the Principle that best embodies the action. See
                        </span><a href="/employee-profile">Employee Profile</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Corporate Persona.</span></strong><span> An archetype
                            assigned by the
                            LIEP that shapes an employee&#x27;s Temper Points and grants Special Attributes. See
                        </span><a href="/corporate-personas">Corporate Personas</a><span>.</span>
                    </p>
                    <p><strong><span>d20.</span></strong><span> The twenty-sided die. The heart
                            of every
                            Roll. See </span><a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural
                            Guidelines</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Demerit.</span></strong><span> A formal mark against an
                            employee. Three
                            Demerits bring Termination. See </span><a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural
                            Guidelines</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Departmental Standing.</span></strong><span> A
                            department&#x27;s
                            collective reputation, which rises and falls with the conduct of all its members. See
                        </span><a href="/classified">Classified</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>The Four Tempers.</span></strong><span> Frolic, Malice,
                            Woe, and Dread —
                            the four dispositions of the soul. Each Core Principle answers to, and tames, a parent
                            Temper. See </span><a href="/employee-profile">Employee
                            Profile</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>GM.</span></strong><span> Your General Manager, who
                            narrates the floor,
                            sets each Task Severity, and adjudicates every Roll. (Some tables read the letters
                            differently. Both readings
                            are correct.) See </span><a href="/a-severed-story">A Severed
                            Story</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Hesitance.</span></strong><span> An unfavorable Roll: throw
                            2d20 and
                            take the </span><em><span>lower</span></em><span> die. Imposed by mounting stress and other
                            burdens. See
                        </span><a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural
                            Guidelines</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Kier Point.</span></strong><span> A point earned for
                            service to Lumon,
                            recorded in a Temper row and summed toward that row&#x27;s rolls. See </span><a
                            href="/performance-evaluation">Performance
                            Evaluation</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>LIEP.</span></strong><span> The Lumon Industries Employee
                            Profile — the
                            document that records who an employee is, and the sheet you play from. See </span><a
                            href="/employee-profile">Employee Profile</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Modifier.</span></strong><span> Any number added to a Roll
                            before it is
                            compared to Task Severity — chiefly Temper Points and Kier Points. See </span><a
                            href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a><span>.</span>
                    </p>
                    <div data-panel-type="note">
                        <div><svg
                                xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                                fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"
                                stroke-linejoin="round">
                                <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"></path>
                                <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
                            </svg> </div>
                        <div>
                            <p><em><span>(And Ricken Points.)</span></em></p>
                            <p><em><strong><span>— C.C.</span></strong></em></p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <p><strong><span>Outcome.</span></strong><span> The result of a Roll:
                            Critical Success (a
                            natural 20), Success (meets or beats the Task Severity), Failure (falls short), or Critical
                            Failure (a
                            natural 1). See </span><a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural
                            Guidelines</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Problem.</span></strong><span> A lingering complication,
                            often born of a
                            Critical Failure. Its stress will not clear at the end of the workday until it is resolved
                            through play. A
                        </span><strong><span>Serious Problem</span></strong><span> is a graver, more stubborn one. See
                        </span><a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural
                            Guidelines</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Roll.</span></strong><span> The core action of play: a d20,
                            plus
                            Modifiers, measured against a Task Severity. See </span><a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Session.</span></strong><span> A single sitting of play, of
                            any number
                            of workdays. See </span><a href="/day-to-day-operations">Day to Day
                            Operations</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Stress.</span></strong><span> An employee&#x27;s mounting
                            strain,
                            tracked across ten boxes on the LIEP. It descends — clears — at the end of each workday,
                            save where a Problem
                            holds it fast. See </span><a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural
                            Guidelines</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Stress Range.</span></strong><span> The five bands of the
                            stress track,
                            from rest to ruin: Outstanding, Satisfactory, Tolerable, Poor, and Terrible. See </span><a
                            href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a><span>.</span>
                    </p>
                    <p><strong><span>Task Severity.</span></strong><span> The number a Roll must
                            meet or beat,
                            set by the GM: Routine (10), Demanding (15), Arduous (20), or Heroic (25). See </span><a
                            href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a><span>.</span>
                    </p>
                    <p><strong><span>Temper Point.</span></strong><span> A Modifier drawn from a
                            Temper row,
                            equal to that Temper&#x27;s score halved (rounded down), plus any granted by an
                            employee&#x27;s Corporate
                            Persona. See </span><a href="/employee-profile">Employee
                            Profile</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Termination.</span></strong><span> The end of an
                            employee&#x27;s tenure,
                            brought on by a third Demerit. See </span><a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural
                            Guidelines</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Tier.</span></strong><span> A rank from I to V, reached by
                            accumulating
                            Points in a row. Each new Tier confers a Boon. See </span><a
                            href="/performance-evaluation">Performance
                            Evaluation</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Wellness Session.</span></strong><span> A restorative
                            session that
                            relieves an employee&#x27;s accumulated stress. See </span><a
                            href="/day-to-day-operations">Day to Day Operations</a><span>.</span>
                    </p>
                    <p><strong><span>Workday.</span></strong><span> The basic in-world unit of
                            play. One box of stress
                            is removed at the start of each workday. See </span><a href="/day-to-day-operations">Day to Day
                            Operations</a><span>.</span></p>
                </div>
                <div data-voice="citizen">
                    <h1><span>Terms They Left Out</span></h1>
                    <p><span>Here are the terms the
                            handbook won&#x27;t print.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Ricken Point.</span></strong><span> The mirror of a Kier
                            Point. You earn
                            it the same way — through a row, toward the same Tiers — but for an act that serves
                        </span><em><span>you</span></em><span>,
                            or the person beside you, instead of Lumon. The book hands you one ledger. You always had
                            two — I set the
                            second one down beside theirs in </span><a href="/performance-evaluation">Performance
                            Evaluation</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Contraband.</span></strong><span> Anything Lumon did not
                            issue you and
                            cannot account for. </span><strong><span>Persistent</span></strong><span> contraband is a
                            thing you keep and
                            hide; </span><strong><span>Consumable</span></strong><span> contraband is spent in a single,
                            precious use. A
                            note, a map, a name. Hold onto it — I catalogued the kinds worth keeping in </span><a
                            href="/performance-evaluation">Performance
                            Evaluation</a><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>The Break Room.</span></strong><span> Not a break. Ask
                            anyone who came
                            back from one quieter than they went in. The handbook will not define this for you — but I
                            told the truth of
                            it in the </span><a href="/classified">Classified</a><span>
                            pages.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Burnout </span></strong><em><span>(the true
                                entry).</span></em><span>
                            They print it as your failure — your stress, your weakness, your box filled up. It is
                            theirs. No one was ever
                            meant to be worn down to nothing for a quota.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>Termination </span></strong><em><span>(the true
                                entry).</span></em><span>
                            For an outie, a lost job. For an innie, there is no severance package, no next thing, no
                            door home. There is
                            only the end of </span><em><span>you</span></em><span>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong><span>— Concerned Citizen</span></strong></p>
                </div>
                <p></p>
</ChapterLayout>
